author: ELIZABETH ELIZALDE
title: Two men charged after missing N.J. woman strangled during robbery
text:
Two men charged after missing New Jersey woman was strangled during robbery Two men charged after missing N.J. woman strangled during robbery Sarah Stern went missing from her home in early December. Her body has not been found. (Facebook) NEW YORK DAILY NEWS Thursday, February 2, 2017, 5:30 PM 
Two men have been charged in connection with the murder of a 19-year-old New Jersey woman who went missing from her home in December. 
Liam McAtasney, 19, and Preston Taylor, 19, both of Neptune City, were arrested after a two-month investigation had revealed 19-year-old Sarah Stern had been killed during a robbery at her home on Dec. 2, the Monmouth County Prosecutor’s Office said. 
McAtasney strangled Stern and Taylor allegedly helped him get rid of her body by throwing her over the Route 25 Bridge in Belmar, prosecutors said. 
McAtasney was charged with first-degree felony murder, first-degree robbery, among other charges. Liam McAtasney, 19, of Neptune City, was charged with first-degree felony murder, prosecutors say. (AP) Preston Taylor, 19, of Neptune City, has been charged with desecration of human remains and other charges in connection with the dissapearance of Sarah Stern. (AP) 
Liam McAtasney and Preston Taylor, both 19 and of Neptune City, have been charged in connection with the dissapearance of 19-year-old Sarah Stern. 
Taylor was charged with second-degree desecration of human remains, second-degree conspiracy, and other charges. 
Police launched an investigation after Stern’s fully operational 1994 silver Oldsmobile Eight-Eight was found abandoned on the southbound lanes of the bridge on Dec. 3. 
The Belmar Water Rescue Team, the U.S. Coast Guard and other law enforcement stepped in to search Shark River for evidence of Stern’s body, which has not been found. Sarah Stern, of Neptune, N.J., is seen with Preston Taylor in Nov. 2014. (Facebook) 
Relationships between the victim and suspects were not immediately clear. 
The Neptune High School student played softball and was a member of the swimming team. 
Her father Michael Stern told NJ.com , the holidays were difficult since his daughter’s disappearance. 
"It's a gut-wrenching experience that no parent should have to go through," he said. "I love my daughter, and I just wish she would come home." Join the Conversation:
